AVIAN INFLUENZA, HUMAN - EAST ASIA (51): DEATH RATE
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: 16 Mar 2005
From: Joseph P. Dudley, Ph.D. <dudley@eurasiagroup.net>

I belive that Dr. Altman's comment in his New York Times article that
"The bottom line is that more human avian influenza may be around
than once suspected, but fewer people who get it become gravely ill
and die than initially predicted" is not only an oversimplification
(as he himself stated) but also potentially misleading as well.
I agree with the author that the existence of undetected asymptomatic
cases may indicate that the mortality/morbidity ratio may indeed be
lower than expected on the basis of the available data.
Nonetheless, Dr. Altman's comments in the article do not appear to
take into account the full implications of the potential additive
mortality as well as morbidity associated with atypical cases
involving gastroenteritis/encephalitis symptoms in the absence of any
associated respiratory syndrome, for which there appear to be no
reliable data other that that such mortality can and has occurred in
at least one known and one suspected case (de Jong et al., 2005 Mew
England J Medicine
<http://content.nejm.org/cgi/content/short/352/7/686>).
I think that what needs to be emphasized in this context is that not
only have more people been infected with H5N1 bird flu than current
official statistics indicate (as detailed in the NY Times article),
but that the number of people who have actually died from both
typical and atypical H5N1 infections -- untested, unnoticed, or
unconfirmed -- is also undoubtedly much higher than the available
data will show.
There is therefore great need to increase both the accuracy of
laboratory confirmations for H5N1 infections in Vietnam, and to
increase the rates of testing of potential atypical cases to
determine the potential frequency and number of human deaths
associated with atypical H5N1 infections involving only gastroenteric
and/or encephalitis symptoms that may have occurred in Vietnam,
Thailand, and potentially elsewhere in Southeast Asia.
--
Joseph P. Dudley, Ph.D.
Eurasia Group
1101 30th Street NW, Suite 100B
Washington, D.C. 20007
<dudley@eurasiagroup.net>
